{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526596"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:23:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.13,0.06,0.68,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53044"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6819"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2403"},{"type":"tags","id":"2981"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15357"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53044"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of recurrent episodes of fever. Two months ago, he underwent emergency surgery (colectomy and splenectomy) after a workplace accident. He had made an uneventful recovery and was now back at work. He has no significant medical history other than the recent surgery and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 124/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Apart from some mild tenderness in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen, the physical examination is normal. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and review in one month","Broad spectrum antibiotics and review in two weeks","Diagnostic laparoscopy","Percutaneous CT-guided drainage","Endoscopic transgastric aspiration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a well-defined, low-density collection in the left subphrenic space, consistent with a subphrenic abscess. This diagnosis is supported by the patient\u0027s history of recent abdominal surgery and presentation with recurrent fever. Subphrenic abscesses are often a complication of abdominal surgery or intra-abdominal infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous CT-guided drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. It is less invasive than open surgical drainage and has a high success rate for uncomplicated abscesses. This procedure allows for both diagnostic (culture of the aspirate) and therapeutic benefits. It is typically combined with antibiotic therapy based on culture results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and review in one month\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for a patient with a subphrenic abscess. This condition requires prompt intervention to prevent complications such as sepsis or rupture into adjacent structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad spectrum antibiotics and review in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient for treating a subphrenic abscess. While antibiotics are an important part of treatment, they need to be combined with drainage of the abscess for effective management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily invasive when the diagnosis is clear from the CT scan. It might be considered if percutaneous drainage fails or if there\u0027s suspicion of a more complex intra-abdominal pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic transgastric aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is a technique sometimes used for pancreatic pseudocysts but is not typically employed for subphrenic abscesses. It would be technically challenging and riskier than percutaneous drainage in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing percutaneous drainage, the patient should receive appropriate antibiotics based on culture results. Close follow-up is essential to ensure resolution of the abscess and to monitor for any complications or recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subphrenic abscesses often present with non-specific symptoms such as recurrent fever and abdominal pain, especially following abdominal surgery.","CT scan is the gold standard for diagnosing subphrenic abscesses.","Percutaneous CT-guided drainage is the first-line treatment for most subphrenic abscesses, offering a less invasive alternative to open surgical drainage."],"references":["Jaffe TA, Nelson RC. Image-guided percutaneous drainage: a review. Abdom Radiol (NY) 2016; 41:629-36. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26826090/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21010"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21010"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/